Varactor analysis of 10X sequenced and Seq-Well sequenced PBMC dataset

In this notebook, we provide an example that Varactor decreases the difference of sequencing technologies, 10X and Seq-Well.

rr rm(list=ls()) library(matrixStats) library(Rtsne) library(dplyr) library(ggplot2) library(RColorBrewer) library(Seurat) library(expm)

Viewing the Seq-Well dataset

We first view the Seq-Well dataset, which is already annotated.

Ref. Gierahn T. Seq-Well: portable, low-cost RNA sequencing of single cells at high throughput. Nature Methods 2017(14).

Load Seq-Well dataset

rr pbmc_well = list() pbmc_well$expr <- read.csv(../data/raw/pbmc_seq_well/GSM2486333_PBMC.txt, sep = , header = T, row.names = 1)

Explore

Apparently, the gene is in HUGO naming and the cells are named after their types.

Viewing and annotating the Seq-Well dataset

The 10X dataset is not annotated, so we follow the procedure in the Seq-Well paper to filter the genes and annotate it.

Jointly analysis using Varactor

Create a Varactor object

rr source(../R/varactor_class.R)

package R6 was built under R version 3.5.3package umap was built under R version 3.5.3

rr obj2 <- Varactor\(new(data = list(x10x = pbmc_10x\)expr, well = pbmc_well\(expr), labels = list(x10x = list(type = as.character(pbmc_10x\)cell_type)), well = list(type = as.character(pbmc_well$cell_type)) ) )

Now you are creating an R6 object.
If you want to make a copy for an R6 object, use 'a_copy <- this_one$clone()'.

Normalize, combine and perform dimensionality reduction

rr obj2$normalize()

Normalizing data for each dataset...
Note that the nomalization is based all the genes available in each dataset.

rr obj2$combine()

Combine data to one single dataset...

rr obj2$reduce()

Calculating PCA...
Dimensionality is set to 50. If this is not preferred provide a value for parameter reduce.
Depending on the data size, this may take a few minutes...
0 constant genes are not considered in PCA.

rr #temp_normalized -> obj2\(normalized #temp_reduced -> obj2\)reduced #temp_combined -> obj2$combined

UMAP analysis

Euclidean distance

Coloring: cell types

rr obj2\(define_metric(\primary\, \euclidean\)\)measure()\(embed(\primary\, \umap\)\)plot_embedding(, , pch=20)

NULL

Coloring: sequencing technologies

rr obj2$plot_embedding(, , pch=20)

NULL

Apparently, difference in technologies are shown heavily in the embedding, hindering our exploration to the biological meanings.

Davidson distance

We use davidson distance to control the difference introduced by the techonology differences.

rr obj2\(define_metric(\alternative\, \davidson\, strata = \sample\)\)measure()\(embed(\alternative\, \umap\)\)plot_embedding(, , pch=20)

NULL

rr obj2$plot_embedding(, , pch=20)

NULL

The cell types are more tightly clustered and the difference between the technologies are decreased.
